properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures well into the minus thirties with light winds will bring periods of extreme wind chills around -50 this morning. These extreme wind chills will moderate later today. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Strong winds are expected to develop through the Richardson Mountains overnight. Winds should ease somewhat for Tuesday afternoon, only to re-intensify overnight Tuesday. The strong winds are expected to lead to periods of reduced visibilities in blowing snow through Wednesday night. Lighter winds are forecast on Thursday. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A deep low pressure system will track across the Gulf of Alaska tonight. A sharp trough extending well to the south of the Low will swing just past Haida Gwaii giving rise to strong southeasterly winds for adjacent regions of British Columbia. We expect the winds to reach up to 100 km/h this evening over Haida Gwaii and North Coast - coastal sections for a few hours until they ease after midnight. These winds will quickly spread to Central Coast - coastal sections late this evening where they will persist through the night before easing early Wednesday morning. ### High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-29T04:58:59-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-01-28T12:59:59-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2003340674.2020

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Strong winds will produce widespread blizzard conditions today. The condition will ease this evening then re-intensify overnight and continue through Wednesday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
